///Lab: DOM-based open redirection///

"Open redirection", so we are searching for a "home" or "back to home page" link, which can be vulnerable...If you click on one of the posts, in the top of the right side there is a "home" link, and
at the bottom right the is a "back to Blog" link, lets check them in source code:
The home link:
<a href="/">Home</a>
The back to Blog link:
<a href="#" onclick="returnUrl = /url=(https?:\/\/.+)/.exec(location); location.href = returnUrl ? returnUrl[1] : &quot;/&quot;">Back to Blog</a>
And the "back to Blog" is the winner. Why?
Because it checks two condition at the same time...is there a "url=xy" parameter in the url or not? in this url is it 'https://' or 'http://' or not? If no is the answer any of them it returns us to the main page.
But if both conditions are right because of the ".+" part, we can write anyithing after https://. So we have to add the url=https//:xyz.com to the url and we won...This url will be our exploit servers url:
